WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
This is how to start exploring and cleaning your data the right way.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.520
When you're starting a new project with a new dataset, it can be tempting to jump straight

00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:11.120
into building a model, but the real magic happens in EDA, or Exploratory Data Analysis.

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:14.920
If you're using positron, the Data Explorer widget makes this super easy.

00:00:14.920 --> 00:00:18.780
Data Explorer gives you instant column summaries to see counts, unique values, and missing

00:00:18.780 --> 00:00:23.000
data without writing a single line of code, data type detection, interactive filtering,

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:24.000
and quick sorting and searching.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.280
You can literally open a dataset, click through the columns, and get a feel for the shape

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:28.280
of your data in seconds.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:32.119
Whether you're using positron or not, these are your non-negotiables before you start

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:33.119
analysis.

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:34.680
First up is to check for missing values.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:37.439
Decide if and how you're filling them, or if you're dropping them.

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:38.540
Confirm what data types you have.

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:41.400
Make sure numbers are numbers, dates are dates, and text is actually text.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:42.400
Look for duplicates.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.000
These can quietly skew your results.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.720
Scan for outliers or weird values.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.439
Sometimes it's a data entry error.

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:48.439
Sometimes it's a real insight.

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:51.759
And lastly, standardize your formats for dates, currency, units.

00:00:51.759 --> 00:00:52.759
This consistency matters.

00:00:52.759 --> 00:00:54.480
Make sure you're following along for more data science content.

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:54.980
Bye!

